24
00:01:17,016 --> 00:01:21,496
It details the impacts of climate change on
indigenous communities all around the world

25
00:01:21,656 --> 00:01:24,356
and features many different
objects from different cultures.

26
00:01:25,246 --> 00:01:30,156
Now, what I've done the summer is develop
some lessons that take all of those stories

27
00:01:30,156 --> 00:01:33,426
and bring them a little bit
closer to home using abalone.

28
00:01:34,446 --> 00:01:36,786
Abalone are type of snail.

29
00:01:36,836 --> 00:01:38,486
They've got these incredible shells,

30
00:01:39,106 --> 00:01:41,906
and the Climate Stories Exhibition
features different objects

31
00:01:41,996 --> 00:01:44,186
from around the world with
different types of shells.

32
00:01:45,146 --> 00:01:48,396
But I wanted to take all of the
stories, bring them here to Bay Area,

33
00:01:48,496 --> 00:01:51,176
because abalone are incredibly
important here in California.

34
00:01:52,046 --> 00:01:55,916
They were not only important for the fishing
industry over the last hundred years or so,

35
00:01:56,366 --> 00:02:01,246
but they've been used for thousands of years by
indigenous communities he's here in California,

36
00:02:01,246 --> 00:02:03,276
including the Ohlone here in the Bay Area.

37
00:02:04,316 --> 00:02:08,906
Now, what I've done is create some lesson
plans that talk about abalone as an animal,

38
00:02:08,906 --> 00:02:14,026
talk about abalone as place in
California history, and some of the ways

39
00:02:14,026 --> 00:02:15,876
that we can protect abalone for the future.

40
00:02:16,876 --> 00:02:19,316
