42
00:02:20,966 --> 00:02:25,276
But in the meantime, I'll show you a quick
kind of craft project you can do at home.

43
00:02:25,536 --> 00:02:29,006
One of the most well-known
features of an abalone is its shell.

44
00:02:29,826 --> 00:02:31,306
Not necessarily the outside though.

45
00:02:32,016 --> 00:02:35,586
The outside of an abalone shell
might be colorful, might be faded,

46
00:02:35,586 --> 00:02:39,496
might be pitted from boring sponges,
it might be covered in algae,

47
00:02:39,496 --> 00:02:42,606
and it might have some hitchhikers,
like barnacles or snails,

48
00:02:43,246 --> 00:02:47,206
but the inside of their shell is rainbow.

49
00:02:47,426 --> 00:02:52,616
They have this incredible iridescent
coloration coming from a structure called nacre,

50
00:02:52,966 --> 00:02:54,746
which we can also call Mother of Pearl.

51
00:02:55,066 --> 00:02:58,136
It makes the shell super
strong and it's really pretty.

52
00:02:58,816 --> 00:03:04,306
Now, we see iridescence in a lot of other
things, in some rocks, for example, feathers,

53
00:03:04,946 --> 00:03:09,376
inside of mussel shells, but not everyone
has all of this iridescent material at home.

54
00:03:10,006 --> 00:03:14,716
So we're going to learn a little bit more about
abalone and their iridescence by making our own.

55
00:03:15,216 --> 00:03:18,846
Now, to do this craft, you will
need a shallow dish of water,

56
00:03:19,176 --> 00:03:22,206
some black paper, and some clear nail polish.

57
00:03:22,896 --> 00:03:27,586
First step is to take your clear nail
polish and gently touch the surface

58
00:03:27,586 --> 00:03:30,646
of the brush to the surface of the water.

59
00:03:32,136 --> 00:03:34,126
Now, you'll see it kind of spread across.

60
00:03:35,696 --> 00:03:40,656
Take your black strip of paper,
gently dunk it in your water

61
00:03:41,136 --> 00:03:43,696
so that the nail polish wraps around the paper.

62
00:03:44,686 --> 00:03:46,856
And then what you have, it's a
little hard to see on camera here,

63
00:03:46,856 --> 00:03:51,386
but you end up with these beautiful
kind of rainbow shimmering strips.

64
00:03:51,386 --> 00:03:53,816
You can kind of see in the light there.

65
00:03:54,546 --> 00:03:59,976
When you let it dry, you can use it as a
bookmark or anything else you can think of.

66
00:04:00,566 --> 00:04:02,886
If you want, you can even
make your own abalone with it.

67
00:04:03,506 --> 00:04:07,206
We have a craft coming to the
Global Museum website soon

68
00:04:07,206 --> 00:04:09,556
to make your own paper mache abalone.

69
00:04:09,556 --> 00:04:14,956
You can see a decorated top of mine here with a
little bit of color, it's red abalone after all,

70
00:04:15,356 --> 00:04:19,946
and some barnacles made out of clay,
some fake moss to act as algae.

71
00:04:20,336 --> 00:04:24,416
And then the ,inside I've covered with
some iridescent paper that I made using

72
00:04:24,686 --> 00:04:26,146
that exact technique I just showed you.

73
00:04:27,126 --> 00:04:32,166
If you make iridescent paper at home or a
paper mache abalone, we'd love to see it.

74
00:04:32,586 --> 00:04:37,476
Stay tuned and keep an eye on the Global
Museum website for more crafts and lessons

75
00:04:37,476 --> 00:04:41,146
